    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That chain reaction is classic \"goblin stacking\" behavior in production, where the first error (the timeout) triggers a secondary failure (the `NameError`) because your code assumes the payment gateway call will always succeed before checking other state variables. The reason this only happens during peak traffic is likely due to resource contention, where the high load causes the payment gateway to be slow, which then cascades into your application's state management failing.\n\nThink of it like a crowded kitchen: when everyone rushes to cook at once, the chef (your code) gets overwhelmed, drops a spoon (the timeout), and then accidentally knocks over a bowl of ingredients (the `NameError`) because they're trying to grab the wrong thing in the chaos.\n\nTo fix this, you need to isolate the payment gateway failure so it doesn't ripple into your core business logic, and perhaps add a \"goblin shield\" (a circuit breaker) to stop the chain reaction before it breaks the whole kitchen.",
