      "content": "Ah, \"goblin stacking\" isn't a standard DevOps term like \"circuit breaker\" or \"rate limiter,\" but it's a very accurate description of what's happening: when one small error (the timeout) attracts a swarm of other errors (the `NameError`) because the system is already stressed, it feels like a goblin is stacking up problems on top of each other.\n\nThe \"goblin shield\" I mentioned is definitely a metaphor for a **Circuit Breaker pattern**, which is a specific architectural design used to prevent cascading failures. Here's how it works:\n\n1.  **The Problem:** When your payment gateway times out, your code tries to do something else (check `state_variable`) assuming the gateway is still alive. This is like a goblin trying to build a tower while the foundation is shaking.\n2.  **The Shield (Circuit Breaker):** Instead of letting the timeout crash your whole logic, the circuit breaker detects the timeout and \"opens the circuit.\" It stops sending requests to the payment gateway for a set time, allowing your system to stay stable even if the gateway is down.\n3.  **The Result:** The \"goblins\" (errors)",
